## The Gold Coast Sanctuary

In 2E 582, the **Dark Brotherhood** maintained several sanctuaries across **Tamriel**, but one of the most active and prestigious was the **Gold Coast Sanctuary**, nestled in the hills of the **Gold Coast**, the fertile region between Cyrodiil and the lands to the west. This sanctuary, hidden behind an enchanted black door accessible only to initiates, housed a community of assassins devoted to the service of **Sithis** and the **Night Mother**.

The Gold Coast Sanctuary took its name from the rich lands surrounding it and, according to some, from the color of the light that filtered into its underground halls at sunset. Contrary to the image of gloomy lairs usually associated with the Brotherhood, this sanctuary possessed a certain austere beauty, its halls decorated with altars to Sithis and tapestries depicting the deeds of past assassins.

Leadership of the sanctuary rested with a **Speaker**, a high-ranking member who served as intermediary between the Night Mother and the sanctuary's brothers and sisters. The Speaker received the Night Mother's commandments — the names of those who had been prayed for through the Black Sacrament — and passed them on to the assassins designated to carry out the contracts.

## The Theology of Death

The Dark Brotherhood was not a simple criminal organization: it was a religious order whose deity was death itself. **Sithis**, the Void, the primordial force of non-existence and entropy, was venerated as the ultimate creator and destroyer of all things. Every assassination committed in the name of the Brotherhood was an act of devotion, an offering to the Void that awaits all things at the end.

The **Night Mother**, spectral bride of Sithis, served as intermediary between the Void and mortals. According to Brotherhood doctrine, she had been a mortal woman who sacrificed her own children to Sithis, and as reward was elevated to the rank of divine mediator. Her mortal body, preserved and venerated, was the channel through which the prayers of the desperate — the Black Sacrament — reached the Brotherhood.

The **Five Tenets** governed the conduct of members: never dishonor the Night Mother, never betray the Brotherhood or its secrets, never disobey the orders of a Speaker, never steal from a brother or sister, and never kill a brother or sister. Violation of these tenets was punished by a visit from the **Wrath of Sithis**, the Brotherhood's spectral executioner who hunted traitors to the ends of Tamriel.

## The Black Sacrament

The process by which a mortal could engage the Brotherhood's services was the **Black Sacrament**, a macabre ritual that served as both prayer and contract. The petitioner had to lock themselves in a room with a human body representing their target, surround it with candles and ritual ingredients, then recite the invocation to the Night Mother while intensely thinking of the person they wished dead.

If the prayer was sincere and the ritual correctly performed, the Night Mother heard the call and transmitted the contract to the Brotherhood. An assassin was then designated to make contact with the petitioner, negotiate payment, and carry out the contract. The process could take days or weeks, but the Brotherhood never refused a contract legitimately commissioned through the Black Sacrament.

Payment varied considerably according to the difficulty of the contract and the petitioner's means. Some paid in gold, others in services, still others in information. The Brotherhood sometimes even accepted contracts from insolvent petitioners, if the death commissioned served the broader interests of Sithis and the Void. Money was merely a means, never an end.

## The Assassins of the Sanctuary

The members of the Gold Coast Sanctuary formed a surprisingly close-knit community despite the nature of their activities. Bound by their shared devotion to Sithis and the shared danger of their profession, brothers and sisters developed intense bonds of loyalty. The sanctuary was their family, often the only one they had ever known, and they protected one another with ferocity proportional to that attachment.

Recruitment happened in several ways. Some were approached after demonstrating a natural talent for killing. Others actively sought out the Brotherhood, drawn by its reputation or an inner calling they could not explain. Others still were orphans or outcasts taken in young and trained in the art of death. All shared one thing in common: a familiarity with death that surpassed that of ordinary mortals.

The training of a Brotherhood assassin was long and rigorous. Beyond combat techniques and infiltration skills, novices studied the alchemy of poisons, the art of disguise, the psychology of the target, and of course the theology of Sithis. A Brotherhood assassin was not a mere hired killer: they were a priest of death, a conscious instrument of the Void's will.

## Operations on the Gold Coast

The Gold Coast, wealthy and politically unstable in 2E 582, offered fertile ground for the Brotherhood's activities. Rival nobles disputed power, merchants betrayed one another for profit, and politicians eliminated their opponents with a regularity that ensured a constant flow of contracts. The Gold Coast Sanctuary never lacked for work.

Contracts in the region varied from simple to complex. Some involved the discreet elimination of a business rival, a dagger in the darkness and a silent disappearance. Others demanded considerable creativity: assassinations disguised as accidents, undetectable poisonings, or murders committed in public without being identified. Each contract was a unique challenge that tested the skills of the designated assassin.

The Brotherhood also maintained complex relationships with local powers. Certain nobles and officials knew perfectly well that the sanctuary existed and tolerated it so long as it did not directly threaten their interests. Others actively sought to destroy it. This perpetual dance between established power and the secret organization was a constant of the Brotherhood's existence throughout the ages.

## The Permanence of the Brotherhood

The Dark Brotherhood of 2E 582 was but one chapter in a history spanning millennia. The organization had survived the falls of empires, religious purges, and internal betrayals, always rising from its ashes like a reflection of the death drive inherent in every mortal society. As long as living beings wished for the death of other living beings, the Brotherhood would have a reason to exist.

The Gold Coast Sanctuary itself would know highs and lows over the centuries. Periods of prosperity alternated with moments of crisis when the sanctuary was discovered, attacked, or betrayed from within. But devotion to Sithis was stronger than any material adversity, and new faithful always rose to take up the torch of fallen assassins.

The theological and operational legacy of the Gold Coast Sanctuary influenced Brotherhood practices for centuries to come. The rituals, the codes, the assassination methods refined over generations were passed down to the sanctuaries of the **Third** and **Fourth Era**, ensuring the continuity of a tradition of sacred death as old as Tamriel's civilization itself.
